      "modality": "text",
      "content": "The figure is a voltage-to-current converter based on an ideal operational amplifier. The inverting input node is \\(v_n\\), the non-inverting input node is \\(v_p\\), and the output is \\(v_o\\). The source \\(v_s\\) drives node \\(v_n\\) through \\(R_1\\) with current \\(i_1\\), and \\(R_2\\) feeds back from \\(v_o\\) to \\(v_n\\) with current \\(i_2\\). The op-amp input currents are \\(i_n\\) and \\(i_p\\), both defined into the input terminals. From \\(v_o\\), resistor \\(R_3\\) connects to node \\(v_L\\) with current \\(i_3\\) downward. Node \\(v_L\\) is directly connected to the non-inverting input, so \\(v_p=v_L\\). From \\(v_L\\) to ground, one branch is \\(R_4\\) carrying \\(i_4\\), and the other branch is load impedance \\(Z_L\\) carrying \\(i_L\\), both downward. Derive \\(i_L/v_s\\) under \\(\\frac{R_2}{R_1R_3}=\\frac{1}{R_4}\\), and show that \\(i_L\\) is independent of \\(Z_L\\). Answer format: a single algebraic expression. Use the variable names specified in the problem and ASCII characters only; do not include units, explanatory text, or an equals sign."
